Industrialization that is occurring focuses on low labor costs and standards, 
with little forward and backward linkages to the rest of their economies 
o  Haunted by civil war and repression – Haiti, El Salvador, Nicaragua, 
Guatemala 
o  And most recently, by natural disasters (Hurricane Mitch in Honduras) 

In Southern Cone (Chile, Argentina, Uruguay, Brazil) and Mexico, prospects 
reasonably good 
o  More affluent, democracy stronger; militaries under control 
o  Although the challenges they face are daunting – systemic crisis in Argentina, 
economic stagnation and an aging population in Uruguay, massive poverty 
and inequality in Brazil and Mexico – they seem better able to confront these 
challenges 
o  Mexico, in particular, enjoys a special relationship with the U.S. because of 
NAFTA; its economic fortunes and business cycle now clearly linked to the 
north rather than the south 

 
More broadly, across the region, there are certainly some discouraging signs 
o  Sluggish economic growth; most people in the region no better off than they were 
two decades ago 
o  Failure of privatization in most countries to produce socially desirable and politically 
defensible result 
o  Absence of philanthropy and civic engagement by elite 
o  Henry Ford, long dead, probably contributes more to social causes in Mexico 
through the Foundation that bears his name than all 10 of Mexico’s 
billionaires 
o  Failure of U.S. policy, so far, to play a positive role (e.g., FTAA) 

 
On the other hand, the are some important encouraging signs, and it seems fit to conclude 
by emphasizing the positive.  I want to focus, in particular, on the development of Latin 
American civil society 
o  The emergence of social movements at the grassroots, that play a role in local 
government 
o 
 in certain municipalities run by the PT in Brazil (e.g., Porto Alegre), 
experiments in participatory budgeting 
o  And transparency in budgets in many states and cities governed by the PAN 
in Mexico; dates back to 1960s in SLP under the civic movement of Dr. 
Salvador Nava, when expenditures and revenues were posted on the wall for 
all to see 
o  Proliferation of independent media 
o  True, broadcasting oligopolies in Chile, Venezuela, Mexico, Brazil, and even 
Argentina, not to mention smaller countries  
o  But efflorescence of local broadcasters and diversity of publications, many of 
which impact politics and contribute to the transparency and accountability of 
government 
o  Coupled with media, increasing growth of the polling industry, so that citizens 
views reflected back to policymakers and to themselves 
o  As Miguel Basañez, essentially the founder of Mexican polling industry put it:  
seeing the country in polling numbers is very different from seeing it in official 
press releases 
o  Anti-corruption groups 
o  Transparency International, an NGO with chapters in almost every country in 
the region 

